"Suparta W., Abdul Rashid Z.A., Mohd. Ali Mohd.A., Yatim B., Fraser G.J.","Observations of Antarctic precipitable water vapor and its response to the solar activity based on GPS sensing",2008,"Journal of Atmospheric and Solar-Terrestrial Physics","70","11-12",,"1419","1447",,,10.1016/j.jastp.2008.04.006,"http://www.scopus.com/inward/record.url?eid=2-s2.0-48049111383&partnerID=40&md5=e05e70f0524b9f476d70591811cd3ba5","Department of Electrical, Electronic and System Engineering, Universiti Kebangsaan Malaysia, 43600 Bangi, Selangor, Malaysia; Institute of Space Science (ANGKASA), Universiti Kebangsaan Malaysia, 43600 Bangi, Selangor, Malaysia; Department of Physics and Astronomy, University of Canterbury, Christchurch, New Zealand","Suparta, W., Department of Electrical, Electronic and System Engineering, Universiti Kebangsaan Malaysia, 43600 Bangi, Selangor, Malaysia, Institute of Space Science (ANGKASA), Universiti Kebangsaan Malaysia, 43600 Bangi, Selangor, Malaysia; Abdul Rashid, Z.A., Department of Electrical, Electronic and System Engineering, Universiti Kebangsaan Malaysia, 43600 Bangi, Selangor, Malaysia; Mohd. Ali, Mohd.A., Department of Electrical, Electronic and System Engineering, Universiti Kebangsaan Malaysia, 43600 Bangi, Selangor, Malaysia; Yatim, B., Institute of Space Science (ANGKASA), Universiti Kebangsaan Malaysia, 43600 Bangi, Selangor, Malaysia; Fraser, G.J., Department of Physics and Astronomy, University of Canterbury, Christchurch, New Zealand","Predicting global climate change is a great challenge and must be based on a thorough understanding of how the climate system components behave. Precipitable water vapor (PWV) is one of the key components in determining and predicting the global climate system. It is well known that the local surface temperature and pressure have a direct influence on the production of PWV. However, the influence of solar activity on atmospheric dynamics and their physical mechanisms is still an open debate, where past studies are focused at mid-latitude regions. A new method of determining and quantifying the solar influence on PWV based on GPS observations to correlate the GPS PWV and total electron content (TEC) variations is proposed. Observed data from Scott Base (SBA) and McMurdo (MCM) stations from 2003 to 2005 have been used to study the response of PWV to solar activity. In the analysis, the effects of local conditions (wind speed and relative humidity) on the distribution of PWV are investigated. Results show significant correlation between PWV and solar activity for four geomagnetic storms, with correlation coefficients of 0.74, 0.77, 0.64 and 0.69, which are all significant at the 95% confidence level. There was no significant correlation between TEC and PWV changes during the absence of storms. On a monthly analysis, a strong relationship exists between PWV and TEC during storm-affected days, with correlation coefficients of 0.83 and 0.89 (99% confidence level) for SBA and MCM respectively. These indicate a statistically significant seasonal signal in the Antarctic region, which is very active (higher) during the summer and inactive (lower) for the winter periods. © 2008 Elsevier Ltd. All rights reserved.","Antarctica; GPS meteorology; PWV-TEC; Solar events","Atmospheric humidity; Atmospherics; Climate change; Climate control; Correlation methods; Forecasting; Geomagnetism; Global positioning system; Magnetism; Modems; Offshore oil well production; Satellite navigation aids; Silicones; Solar energy; Solar radiation; Storms; Vapors; Well stimulation; Wind effects; Atmospheric dynamics; Climate systems; Confidence level (CL); Correlation coefficient (CC); Elsevier (CO); Geomagnetic storms; Global climate changes; Global climate system; key components; Latitude (CO); Local conditions; New methods; Observed data; physical mechanisms; Precipitable water vapor (PWV); Relative humidity (RH); Solar activity (SA); Solar influence; surface temperatures; Total electron content (TEC); Wind speed (WS); Water vapor",,,,,,"Abdul Rashid, Z.A., Momani, M.A., Sulaiman, S., Mohd Ali, M.A., Yatim, B., Fraser, G., Sato, N., GPS ionospheric TEC measurement during the 23rd November 2003 total solar eclipse at Scott Base Antarctica (2006) Journal of Atmospheric and Solar-Terrestrial Physics, 68 (11), pp. 1222-1236; Alber, C., Ware, R., Rocken, C., Solheim, F., GPS surveying with 1 mm precision using corrections for atmospheric slant path delay (1997) Geophysical Research Letters, 24 (15), pp. 1859-1862; Bevis, M., Businger, S., Herring, T.A., Rocken, C., Anthes, R.A., Ware, R.H., GPS meteorology: remote sensing of atmospheric water vapor using the Global Positioning System (1992) Journal of Geophysical Research, 97 (D14), pp. 15787-15801; Bevis, M., Businger, S., Chiswell, S., GPS meteorology: mapping zenith wet delays onto precipitable water (1994) Journal of Applied Meteorology, 33 (3), pp. 379-386; Businger, S., Chiswell, S.R., Bevis, M., Duan, J., Anthes, R.A., Rocken, C., Ware, R.H., Solheim, F.S., The promise of GPS in atmospheric monitoring (1996) Bulletin of the American Meteorological Society, 77 (1), pp. 5-18; Butler, C.J., Johnston, D.J., A provisional long mean air temperature series from Armagh Observatory (1996) Journal of Atmospheric and Solar-Terrestrial Physics, 58 (15), pp. 1657-1672; Chertok, I.M., Fomichev, V.V., Gnezdilov, A.A., Gorgutsa, R.V., Markeev, A.K., Sobolev, D.E., Violent solar events of October-November 2003 as recorded by IZMIRAN radio observations (2005) Astronomy and Astrophysics Transactions, 24 (1), pp. 45-52; Danilov, A.D., Lastovicka, J., Effects of geomagnetic storms on the ionosphere and atmosphere (2001) International Journal of Geomagnetism and Aeronomy, 2 (3), pp. 194-209; Davis, J.L., Herring, T.A., Shapiro, I.I., Rogres, A.E.E., Elgered, G., Geodesy by radio interferometry: effects of atmospheric modeling errors on estimates of baseline length (1985) Radio Science, 20, pp. 1593-1607; Duan, J., Bevis, M., 